We see that Assault has a much larger variance than the other variables. It would dominate the principal components simply because of the variable units, so we choose to standardize the variables when we perform PCA.

pca.out=prcomp(USArrests,scale=TRUE)
# call to prcomp with scale=TRUE will standardize
# variables for you
pca.out
## Standard deviations (1, .., p=4):
## [1] 1.5748783 0.9948694 0.5971291 0.4164494
## 
## Rotation (n x k) = (4 x 4):
##                 PC1        PC2        PC3         PC4
## Murder   -0.5358995  0.4181809 -0.3412327  0.64922780
## Assault  -0.5831836  0.1879856 -0.2681484 -0.74340748
## UrbanPop -0.2781909 -0.8728062 -0.3780158  0.13387773
## Rape     -0.5434321 -0.1673186  0.8177779  0.08902432
# shows standard deviation for each of the PCs
# and rotation (or loading) for each variable
# 1st PC has roughly equal loading across types of crime
# 2nd PC has high loading on urban population
names(pca.out)
## [1] "sdev"     "rotation" "center"   "scale"    "x"
biplot(pca.out,scale=0,cex=0.6)

# plot shows outcome of PCA, with each observation
# variable (states, black) positioned according to its
# individual contribution in the PCA;
# red shows the loading on each of the PCs: 3 types of 
# crime describe well the 1st PC (axis PC1)
# while urban population describes the 2nd PC (axis PC2)

K-Means Clustering

K-means works in any dimension, but it is most easily demonstrated in two dimensions with plotting. Lets make some fake data with clusters, which we do by shifting the means of randomly generated points.

set.seed(101)
x=matrix(rnorm(100*2),100,2)
# create a matrix of 100*2 randomly uniform points 
# with shape 100x2 rows by columns
xmean=matrix(rnorm(8,sd=4),4,2)
# generate 2 different means for 4 clusters with 
# standard deviation 4; so a 4x2 rows by columns matrix
which=sample(1:4,100,replace=TRUE)
# create set of 100 indices sampled from 1 to 4
x=x+xmean[which,]
# add appropriate mean to approriate rows
# xmean[which,] will choose a mean from xmean
# depending on the row index in `which` and the column
# index in `x`
plot(x,col=which,pch=19)

# try this plot command before and after the line
# `x=x+xmean[which,] to see the effect of making clusters

We know the true cluster IDs, but we will use the kmeans algorithm to try to reproduce them unsupervised.

km.out=kmeans(x,4,nstart=15)
# call kmeans on x and tell it to find 4 clusters;
# nstart is a random start number, which can give 
# bad results if improperly chosen
km.out
## K-means clustering with 4 clusters of sizes 21, 30, 32, 17
## 
## Cluster means:
##         [,1]       [,2]
## 1 -3.1068542  1.1213302
## 2  1.7226318 -0.2584919
## 3 -5.5818142  3.3684991
## 4 -0.6148368  4.8861032
## 
## Clustering vector:
##   [1] 2 3 3 4 1 1 4 3 2 3 2 1 1 3 1 1 2 3 3 2 2 3 1 3 1 1 2 2 3 1 1 4 3 1 3
##  [36] 3 1 2 2 3 2 2 3 3 1 3 1 3 4 2 1 2 2 4 3 3 2 2 3 2 1 2 3 4 2 4 3 4 4 2
##  [71] 2 4 3 2 3 4 4 2 2 1 2 4 4 3 3 2 3 3 1 2 3 2 4 4 4 2 3 3 1 1
## 
## Within cluster sum of squares by cluster:
## [1] 30.82790 54.48008 71.98228 21.04952
##  (between_SS / total_SS =  87.6 %)
## 
## Available components:
## 
## [1] "cluster"      "centers"      "totss"        "withinss"    
## [5] "tot.withinss" "betweenss"    "size"         "iter"        
## [9] "ifault"
# prints cluster size and means of 4 clusters, 
# the custer vector describing the assignment of 
# each point to a cluster, the within cluster
# sum of squares, the between-cluster sum of sqaures
# compared to the total sum of sqaures (a measure
# of the variance explained by the cluster means:
# higher is better)
plot(x,col=km.out$cluster,cex=2,pch=1,lwd=2)
# can see the result of the K-means clustering
points(x,col=which,pch=19)
# compare it to the original data points
# note: color mismatch
points(x,col=c(4,3,2,1)[which],pch=19)

# replot with matched colors
# note: one point originally in the black 
# cluster has been assigned to green by K-means,
# similar for one blue point assigned to black

Heirarchical Clustering

We will use the same data but this time try heirarchical clustering.

hc.complete=hclust(dist(x),method='complete')
# dist(x) computes the distance of x in a 100x100
# pairwise distance matrix; make a call to `hclust`
# for heirarchical clustering
# here 'complete' method uses farthest point in each
# cluster to determine cluster distance
plot(hc.complete)

# plots a dendrogram to show the clustering results;
# heights of the arms of the dendrogram clearly
# show 4 quite distinct clusters
hc.single=hclust(dist(x),method='single')
# here 'single' method uses closest point in each
# cluster to determine cluster distance
plot(hc.single)

# notice here that the clusters are not as clearly
# defined and 'single' seems to find 3 main clusters;
# 'single' method tends to find long, stringy clusters
# due to the shortest point-point distance measurement
hc.average=hclust(dist(x),method='average')
# here 'average' method uses average of point positions 
# in each cluster to determine cluster distance
plot(hc.average)

# results are somewhere in between 'complete' and 'single'

Lets compare this with the actual clusters in the data. We will use the function cutree to cut the tree at level 4. This will produce a vector of numbers from 1 to 4, saying which branch each observation is on. You will sometimes see pretty plots where the leaves of the dendrogram are colored.

We can use table to see how well they match.

hc.cut=cutree(hc.complete,4)
# with `cutree` you give it the hclust results and
# a cutoff point, here we cut at 4 clusters
table(hc.cut,which)
##       which
## hc.cut  1  2  3  4
##      1  0  0 30  0
##      2  1 31  0  2
##      3 17  0  0  0
##      4  0  0  0 19
# creating table from results of `cutree` and the
# true assignments of the data given by which in this
# demonstration (table order is arbitrary);
# in the table there should be 4 large numbers corresponding
# to points contained in the 4 clusters, with zeros
# elsewhere; we see the expected 4 large numbers 
# and a few small numbers that tell us there 
# are some misclassifications from heirarchical clustering
table(hc.cut,km.out$cluster)
##       
## hc.cut  1  2  3  4
##      1  0 30  0  0
##      2  2  0 32  0
##      3  0  0  0 17
##      4 19  0  0  0
# compares the results of heirarchical vs. K-means
# clustering showing disagreement on two points,
# but mostly consistent

or we can use our group membership as labels for the leaves of the dendrogram:

plot(hc.complete,labels=which)

# uses the true cluster assignments from which
# and compares to the leaves of the dendrogram
# from heirarchical clustering method
